Deep Research Plan — AI Vehicle Deal Intelligence Platform
Overview
This issue defines the deep research scope required to design and build an AI-powered vehicle deal intelligence platform.

The goal is to determine the best architecture, data sources, scoring models, and product surface before development begins.

This research will guide the implementation of a web-first car shopping assistant that evaluates used vehicle listings and helps users determine whether a car is a good deal, overpriced, risky, or suspicious.

Product Vision
The platform will help users answer one simple but high-stakes question:

"Should I buy this car at this price with this mileage?"

The system will analyze used car listings and generate a structured evaluation report containing:

Deal score

Reliability insights

Scam / risk flags

Recall data

Inspection checklist

Negotiation suggestions

The product aims to replace hours of manual research across forums, KBB, and recall databases with a single analysis engine.

Primary Capabilities
1. Listing Analysis
Users will provide information about a listing such as:

Listing text

VIN (optional)

Price

Mileage

Location

Year / Make / Model

The system will analyze the listing and determine:

Deal quality (good / fair / overpriced)

Potential risk factors

Reliability concerns

Suggested negotiation strategy

2. Reliability Engine
A reliability analysis system that evaluates:

Known issues by make / model / year

Typical failure points

Ownership risk level

Estimated reliability tier

The reliability engine must use structured data and rules, not AI hallucination.

AI may assist in explaining results, but not generating them.

3. Vehicle Library
A browsable vehicle knowledge base containing:

make

model

year

trim

reliability category

common problems

typical price ranges

This database powers both:

the listing analysis engine

a searchable car research interface

4. User Profiles
Users may complete a car preference quiz to build a profile including:

budget

reliability tolerance

preferred brands

preferred vehicle types

Future features may include:

deal alerts

suggested offers

personalized recommendations

Research Objectives
The research should answer the critical architectural and product questions required to build the platform.

Product Architecture
Determine the best product surface for the first version:

Standalone web application

Browser extension

Hybrid system (web app + extension)

Evaluate tradeoffs including:

development complexity

long-term maintainability

user experience

reliability

marketplace integration limitations

Marketplace Listing Analysis
Investigate reliable methods for analyzing listings from marketplaces such as:

Facebook Marketplace

Craigslist

Autotrader

CarGurus

Focus on approaches that avoid brittle scraping or platform violations.

Possible approaches include:

user-pasted listing text

structured listing inputs

browser extension parsing

Deal Evaluation Models
Research how existing platforms determine vehicle value, including:

Kelley Blue Book

Edmunds

CarGurus

AutoTempest

Key factors to investigate:

price vs mileage adjustments

regional pricing differences

depreciation curves

condition assumptions

market supply / demand effects

Goal: design a transparent and explainable deal scoring system.

Reliability Scoring
Research available data sources that can support a reliability scoring engine.

Possible sources include:

NHTSA recall data

vehicle defect databases

repair frequency datasets

public vehicle reliability studies

large-scale automotive forums

The goal is to create a rules-based reliability engine.

